         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">6/5/90. ¶ This day, dear Prof Watson, arrived the new edition of Gray's Manuel, ¶ Manual? i.e. A. Gray (1890). ¶  which you in conjunction with Prof Coulter and with the aid of local workers have been...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">90.05.06</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Sereno Watson</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">Gray Herbarium Archives, Harvard University, Cambridge, Massachusetts.</seg>
               <seg style=""/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="">MS black-edged; M's brother-in-law George Doughty died on 26 March 1890.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>6/5/90.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This day, dear Prof Watson, arrived the new edition of Gray's Manuel,</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg style="">Manual? i.e. A. Gray (1890).</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> which you in conjunction with Prof Coulter and with the aid of local workers have been able to issue. It is a worthy following up of your great preceptor's work in this particular direction. I presume, you will gradually take in the evascular Acotyledoneae also, as you commenced to do with the Jungermanniaceae. You doubtless felt reluctant, to make at once any great change in the systematic arrangement out of piety to Asa Gray, who in his turn was unwilling to depart from the sequence of the orders as reversed merely from Jussieu by D.C.</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg style="">A. P. de Candolle.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> — But you will concede, that a natural system cannot be perfect, so long as the <name key="Apetaleae">Apetaleae</name> are kept by themselves. If we only think of the unnatural position e.g. of <name key="Salsolaceae">Salsolaceae</name>, kept nearly at one end of the Dicotyledoneae, while <name key="Caryophylleae">Caryophylleae</name> are near the other end! The <name key="Salsolaceae">Salsolaceae</name>, as we are all aware, are only less developed <name key="Curvembryonatae">Curvembryonatae</name> (or <name key="Amyliferae">Amyliferae</name>), just as <name key="Dodonaea">Dodonaea</name> in <name key="Sapindaceae">Sapindaceae</name>, <name key="Alchemilla">Alchemilla</name> in <name key="Rosaceae">Rosaceae</name>, <name key="Anemone">Anemone</name> in <name key="Ranunculaceae">Ranunculaceae</name>, <name key="Glaux">Glaux</name> in <name key="Primulaceae">Primulaceae</name> &amp;c &amp;c. Since the last 25 years I have abolished the <name key="Monochlamydeae">Monochlamydeae</name> in all my writings as such, and I can use the "Census"</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg style="">B83.03.04.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> with far more facility than the "Flora Austral."</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg style="">Bentham (1863-78).</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> This day I have posted to Prof Coulter the "second Census",</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg style="">B89.12.03, an enlarged edition of B83.03.04.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> so that he may see my arrangements, as emanating from the study of Australian plants since 50 years (if I include, what I observed from 1840-1846 on plants of Australia in European gardens.) Perhaps you like to send to your Collaborator this letter, as it may lead you to consultations, whether the change, recommended by me, could be adopted for further editions of the Manual.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Have you a specimen of <name key="Buckleya">Buckleya</name> to spare? I have long been eager to examine its structure myself.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">If your aquatic Jussieua has the petals quite yellow it will likely be J. diffusa, as the genuine J. repens has the petals white except the base; </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">that</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style=""> plant has never yet been found in Australia.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg style="">
                  <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Can <name key="Hydrocotyle%20interrupta">Hydrocotyle interrupta</name> always be distinguished from H. vulgaris?</seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                     <p rend="Footnote"
                        style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <seg style="">The sentence is in the centre margin of the second sheet, between pages 6 and 7.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
